igate and Banstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hackney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Hackney in Greater London, named from an Old English personal name <i>Haca</i> (genitive <i>Hacan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, dry ground in marshland’.","perhaps from Middle English <i>hakenei</i> (Old French <i>haquenée</i>), an ambling horse or mare, especially one considered suitable for women to ride; perhaps therefore a metonymic occupational name for a breeder or keeper of such horses and short for <i>Hakeneyman</i>. This surname has also been found in Scotland since medieval times."],"variants":[{"name":"Oakley","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands): habitational name from any of numerous places called Oakley, Oakle, or Oakleigh, in Bedfordshire, Essex, Gloucestershire, Hampshire, Kent, Somerset, Suffolk, or Wiltshire. The placenames derive from Old English <i>āc</i> ‘oak’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘open woodland’."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Marie</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moira","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Máire , now used throughout the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":46,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":55,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":66,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Hackney was born about 1503, in Horsham, Sussex, England, her father, Thomas Hackney, was 19 and her mother, Mrs Thomas Hackney, was 20. She married Frederick Elsick in 1519, in Horsham, Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1570, in Horley, Surrey, England, at the age of 68, and was buried in Reigate and Banstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1503–1570":"umbes 1503–1570","1503–1570":"1503–1570","1500–1590":"1500–1590","1520–1600":"1520–1600","1538–1604":"1538–1604","1485–1502":"1485–1502","1485–Female":"1485–Surnud","Aft 1502":"pärast 1502","1570":"1570","1590":"1590","1 February 1538":"1. veebruar 1538","Abt 1503":"umbes 1503","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1503":"1503","1502":"1502","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1485":"1485","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","1604":"1604","1538":"1538","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Horsham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Horsham, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Horsham, Horsham District, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Horsham, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Horsham, Sussex, England":"Horsham, Sussex, England","Horley, Surrey, England":"Horley, Surrey, England","Reigate and Banstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Reigate and Banstead, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1503–1570":"noin 1503–1570","1503–1570":"1503–1570","1500–1590":"15